17. What is the difference between WHERE and HAVING?

Answer

WHERE and HAVING clauses are both used for filtering data in MySQL, but they are used in different situations.

WHERE Clause
• Filters rows before grouping
• Used with SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE
• Cannot use aggregate functions directly
• Works on individual rows

HAVING Clause
• Filters data after grouping
• Mainly used with GROUP BY
• Can use aggregate functions
• Works on grouped records

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of WHERE

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE condition;

Example

SELECT * FROM employees
WHERE salary > 50000;

Explanation
• Filters employees whose salary is greater than 50000.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of HAVING

SELECT column_name, aggregate_function(column_name)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY column_name
HAVING condition;

Example

SELECT department, COUNT(*)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 2;

Explanation
• Displays departments having more than 2 employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_Name      Department      Salary
Rahul              IT              60000
Priya              HR              45000
Arjun              IT              70000
Sneha              Finance         55000
Kiran              IT              65000

WHERE Example

SELECT * FROM employees
WHERE salary > 50000;

Output

Rahul
Arjun
Sneha
Kiran

Explanation
• Filters rows before grouping.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HAVING Example

SELECT department, COUNT(*)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 2;

Output

IT      3

Explanation
• Filters grouped data after applying GROUP BY.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

WHERE
• Filters rows
• Used before GROUP BY
• Cannot use aggregate functions

HAVING
• Filters groups
• Used after GROUP BY
• Can use aggregate functions

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Point

• WHERE is used for row-level filtering.
• HAVING is used for group-level filtering.
• HAVING is mostly used with aggregate functions like COUNT(), SUM(), AVG().

