19. What are Aggregate Functions? List five examples.

 Answer

Aggregate Functions in MySQL are used to perform calculations on multiple rows of data and return a single value.

These functions are mainly used with numerical data and are often combined with the GROUP BY clause.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Common Aggregate Functions

COUNT()
• Counts total number of rows

SUM()
• Calculates total sum of values

AVG()
• Finds average value

MAX()
• Finds highest value

MIN()
• Finds lowest value

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of COUNT()

SELECT COUNT(column_name)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM employees;

Explanation
• Counts total number of employees in the table.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of SUM()

SELECT SUM(column_name)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT SUM(salary) FROM employees;

Explanation
• Calculates total salary of all employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of AVG()

SELECT AVG(column_name)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees;

Explanation
• Finds average salary of employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of MAX()

SELECT MAX(column_name)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT MAX(salary) FROM employees;

Explanation
• Displays highest salary among employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Syntax of MIN()

SELECT MIN(column_name)
FROM table_name;

Example

SELECT MIN(salary) FROM employees;

Explanation
• Displays lowest salary among employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Real-Time Example

Consider an Employee Table.

Employee_Name      Department      Salary
Rahul              IT              60000
Priya              HR              45000
Arjun              IT              70000
Sneha              Finance         55000
Kiran              IT              65000

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COUNT() Example

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM employees;

Output

5

Explanation
• Total number of employees is 5.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

SUM() Example

SELECT SUM(salary) FROM employees;

Output

295000

Explanation
• Displays total salary of all employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

AVG() Example

SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees;

Output

59000

Explanation
• Displays average salary of employees.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

MAX() Example

SELECT MAX(salary) FROM employees;

Output

70000

Explanation
• Displays highest salary.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

MIN() Example

SELECT MIN(salary) FROM employees;

Output

45000

Explanation
• Displays lowest salary.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Aggregate Functions with GROUP BY

SELECT department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;

Explanation
• Displays average salary department-wise.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Important Points

• Aggregate functions work on multiple rows.
• They return a single value.
• Mostly used with GROUP BY clause.
• Useful for reports and data analysis.
• Common aggregate functions are COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MAX(), and MIN().

